riendship readily accessible.The book is divided into three sections. The first centers on the nature of friendship, the difference between friendship and other personal loves, and the importance of friendship in the individual's life. The second section discusses the moral significance of friendship and the response of various ethical theories and theorists (Aristotelian, Christian, Kantian, and consequentialist) to the phenomenon of friendship. The last section deals with the importance of personal and civic friendship in a good society. Badhwar's introduction is a comprehensive critical discussion of the issues raised by the essays: it relates them to each other, as well as to historical and contemporary discussions not included in the anthology, thus providing the reader with an integrated overview of the essays and their place in the larger philosophical picture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFriendship. 4aHistory. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnnas, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadhwar, Neera Kapur, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBaron, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlum, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBranden, Nathaniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapur Badhwar, Neera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, C. S., econtributor.4ctb4https://i